column43: IGF::OT::IGF PARTNERSHIPS FORT PEACE TASK ORDER. THE GOAL OF THIS ACTIVITY IS TO SUPPORT THE EFFORTS OF WEST AFRICANS TO IMPROVE THEIR ABILITY TO COUNTER VIOLENT EXTREMISM (CVE). THIS WILL BE ACHIEVED BY IDENTIFYING REGIONAL, NATIONAL, AND SUB-NATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS AND GOVERNMENTS WITH POTENTIAL AND POLITICAL WILL TO COUNTER VE, AND PROVIDING THEM WITH THE ORGANIZATIONAL AND TECHNICAL SKILLS TO UNDERTAKE PROACTIVE CVE PROGRAMS CAPABLE OF DIMINISHING THE VULNERABILITY OF AT-RISK POPULATIONS.
column45: OTHER SCIENTIFIC AND TECHNICAL CONSULTING SERVICES
column54: KARUNA CENTER FOR PEACE BUILDING INC
column76:
Lead regional- and national-level assessments to evaluate the current political context regionally and within the four countries to support the development of P4P's optimal approach to future CVE initiatives.
   Regional conferences and/or consultations which would include government actors responsible for creating national platforms for CVE, national civil society leaders identified as key opinion leaders during the assessment (including religious leaders, youth leaders, journalists, and women s networks), and appropriate representatives from ECOWAS, the Sahel 5, WANEP, WACSOF, and regional partners.  
   Multi-stakeholder dialogues. Regional multi-stakeholder dialogues focusing on horizontal exchange and learning, time will also be given for presentations by international experts on a variety of relevant CVE topics. These dialogues will take place in at least one of the target countries. 
   Final lessons-learned conference. The final multi-stakeholder meeting will be a lessons learned conference and will take place in the region. The emphasis will be on collecting success stories, the further distillation of best practices, and ways of institutionalizing CVE as a crosscutting, integrated effort in both government and civil society peacebuilding practices.  
   Pause and reflect moments. 
 
 Karuna will support iterative learning through ongoing assessment and pause-and-reflect moments throughout the program.  Through weekly or bi-monthly check-ins with Creative and Search for Common Ground staff, both in the field and at respective headquarters, Karuna will provide input to the strategy and activities of the program. Activities could include conferences, capacity building, training, dialogues, etc. at the regional, national, and sub-national levels. While Karuna leads activities under this Output, Creative will approve activities in advance and assist with coordination and collaboration among stakeholders, USAID, regional partners, and other subcontractors.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF OTHER FUNCTIONS THIS CONTRACT IS FOR (R&D) PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTCHNOLOGY) AND IS FOR THE PURCHASE OF SUPPORT SERVICES FOR ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE THE NASA GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER (GSFC) CONDUCTS A COMPREHENSIVE RESEARCH AND TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM DIRECTED TOWARDS OBSERVING, MONITORING, CHARACTERIZING, MODELING, UNDERSTANDING, AND ADVANCING KNOWLEDGE OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE.  THE RESEARCH PROGRAM IS AIMED AT UNDERSTANDING THE STRUCTURE, DYNAMICS, AND RADIATIVE PROPERTIES OF CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, AND PRECIPITATION; UNDERSTANDING ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY, ESPECIALLY THE ROLE OF NATURAL AND ANTHROPOGENIC TRACE SPECIES ON THE OZONE BALANCE IN THE STRATOSPHERE AND TROPOSPHERE; IMPROVING SHORT AND MEDIUM TERM NUMERICAL WEATHER PREDICTION; UNDERSTANDING THE INFLUENCE OF SOLAR VARIABILITY ON THE EARTH'S CLIMATE; AND ADVANCING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE INCLUDING ITS INTERACTION WITH THE EARTH SURFACE.  SCIENTISTS IDENTIFY REQUIREMENTS FOR ATMOSPHERIC OBSERVATIONS VIA SATELLITE MISSIONS AND SUB-ORBITAL INSTRUMENTATION.  SCIENTISTS CONCEIVE, DESIGN, DEVELOP, AND IMPLEMENT OPTICAL, MICROWAVE, RADAR, AND LIDAR TECHNOLOGIES FOR REMOTE SENSING OF THE ATMOSPHERE.  SCIENTISTS FURTHER CONDUCT FIELD MEASUREMENTS FOR SATELLITE SENSOR CALIBRATION AND DATA VALIDATION, AND CARRY OUT MODELING ACTIVITIES FOR ATMOSPHERIC RADIATIVE TRANSFER, CLIMATE, CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, CHEMISTRY AND TRANSPORT OF TRACE SPECIES, AND IN GENERAL THE DEVELOPMENT OF NEXT-GENERATION EARTH SYSTEM MODELS.
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTECHNOLOGY)
column76:
This task supports the maintenance, field support, and processing for radar instruments. Specific efforts under this task include the following:
 
  Work with engineering team members to upgrade the radar systems
  Perform mechanical engineering, analysis, and fabrication for the Goddard radars that is required for new installations, etc.  For all design tasks, any engineering drawings that will be required will be created IAW best industry practices and to a Level II standard, creation of Level III drawings are not required.
  Support development of interface and other boards for the Goddard radars.
  Implement new advanced radar algorithms for airborne and spaceborne radars.
  Travel in support of field campaigns as needed.
 
 The subcontractor shall provide support to the GSFC SpaceCube2.0 radar. NASA Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC) has developed a high speed FPGA based digital receiver for the future spaceborne atmospheric radar, such as the Cyclone Precipitation Process System (CycloPPS) Ka/W-band dual-frequency radar.  The objective of this task is to port the iRAP digital receiver FPGA firmware currently used by the GSFC High-altitude Imaging Wind and Rain Airborne Profiler (HIWRAP) to the newly developed GSFC SpaceCube2.0-based digital receiver board, and to provide support for testing and evaluating the performance of this firmware on the new hardware.

column43: THE ACADEMY OF PROGRAM/PROJECT AND ENGINEERING LEADERSHIP (APPEL) IS LOCATED WITHIN NASA'S OCE AND IS RESPONSIBLE FOR DEVELOPING NASA'S TECHNICAL WORKFORCE IN THREE MAIN AREAS OF PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT: (1) PROGRAM/PROJECT MANAGEMENT, (2) SYSTEMS ENGINEERING, AND (3) ENGINEERING. APPEL ACCOMPLISHES THIS THROUGH THREE MAJOR LINES OF BUSINESS:  1. CURRICULUM DEVELOPMENT (COURSEWORK IN PROGRAM/PROJECT MANAGEMENT, SYSTEMS ENGINEERING, AND ENGINEERING) LIES AT THE HEART OF APPEL'S APPROACH TO BUILDING PROGRAM/PROJECT, ENGINEERING, AND SYSTEMS ENGINEERING CAPABILITY AT NASA. THE COURSES ARE DESIGNED USING PROJECT MANAGEMENT AND SYSTEMS ENGINEERING COMPETENCY MODELS AND FOCUS ON WHAT THE PARTICIPANTS WILL NEED TO ENHANCE THEIR OWN CAPABILITIES, KNOWLEDGE, AND SKILLS. THE ACADEMY'S CURRICULUM EMPLOYS STATE-OF-THE ART METHODOLOGIES BASED ON THE BEST EMPIRICAL RESEARCH AND THE LATEST DEVELOPMENTS IN INDUSTRY. THE OBJECTIVE IS TO SET THE STANDARD FOR TRAINING AND DEVELOPMENT FOR ENGINEERING AND PROJECT MANAGEMENT, THUS ADVANCING THE MISSION OF NASA IN ITS SERVICE OF OUR NATION. 2. KNOWLEDGE SHARING (HOSTING FORUMS AND CONFERENCES, PROVIDING CASE STUDIES, PUBLISHING RELEVANT ARTICLES ON THE APPEL WEBSITE AND OTHER ELECTRONIC AND HARDCOPY VENUES, ETC) PROMOTES EXCELLENCE IN PROJECT MANAGEMENT AND ENGINEERING LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT. ITS PRIMARY STRATEGY FOCUSES ON GATHERING AND SHARING KNOWLEDGE AND WISDOM FROM THE BEST PROGRAM/PROJECT AND ENGINEERING LEADERS ACROSS THE AGENCY. THIS INITIATIVE HAS PROVEN TO BE AN EFFECTIVE CATALYST IN BUILDING AND SUPPORTING ONGOING NASA COMMUNITIES OF PRACTICE. 3. PERFORMANCE ENHANCEMENT (CONSULTING AND COACHING WITH PROGRAM/PROJECT TEAMS) INCREASES A PROJECT'S PROBABILITY OF SUCCESS BY DELIVERING THE RIGHT SUPPORT TO A PROJECT TEAM AT THE RIGHT TIME. THROUGH ONE-ON-ONE ASSISTANCE, FOCUSED WORKSHOPS, OR LARGE-GROUP SESSIONS, PROJECT ENHANCEMENT PROGRAMS ACHIEVE IMMEDIATE PROJECT GOALS, WHILE ENHANCING LONG-TERM TEAM CAPABILITIES.

column76: APPEL Support Services

column43: IGF::OT::IGF OTHER FUNCTIONS THIS CONTRACT IS FOR (R&D) PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTCHNOLOGY) AND IS FOR THE PURCHASE OF SUPPORT SERVICES FOR ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE THE NASA GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER (GSFC) CONDUCTS A COMPREHENSIVE RESEARCH AND TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM DIRECTED TOWARDS OBSERVING, MONITORING, CHARACTERIZING, MODELING, UNDERSTANDING, AND ADVANCING KNOWLEDGE OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE.  THE RESEARCH PROGRAM IS AIMED AT UNDERSTANDING THE STRUCTURE, DYNAMICS, AND RADIATIVE PROPERTIES OF CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, AND PRECIPITATION; UNDERSTANDING ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY, ESPECIALLY THE ROLE OF NATURAL AND ANTHROPOGENIC TRACE SPECIES ON THE OZONE BALANCE IN THE STRATOSPHERE AND TROPOSPHERE; IMPROVING SHORT AND MEDIUM TERM NUMERICAL WEATHER PREDICTION; UNDERSTANDING THE INFLUENCE OF SOLAR VARIABILITY ON THE EARTH'S CLIMATE; AND ADVANCING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE INCLUDING ITS INTERACTION WITH THE EARTH SURFACE.  SCIENTISTS IDENTIFY REQUIREMENTS FOR ATMOSPHERIC OBSERVATIONS VIA SATELLITE MISSIONS AND SUB-ORBITAL INSTRUMENTATION.  SCIENTISTS CONCEIVE, DESIGN, DEVELOP, AND IMPLEMENT OPTICAL, MICROWAVE, RADAR, AND LIDAR TECHNOLOGIES FOR REMOTE SENSING OF THE ATMOSPHERE.  SCIENTISTS FURTHER CONDUCT FIELD MEASUREMENTS FOR SATELLITE SENSOR CALIBRATION AND DATA VALIDATION, AND CARRY OUT MODELING ACTIVITIES FOR ATMOSPHERIC RADIATIVE TRANSFER, CLIMATE, CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, CHEMISTRY AND TRANSPORT OF TRACE SPECIES, AND IN GENERAL THE DEVELOPMENT OF NEXT-GENERATION EARTH SYSTEM MODELS.

THIS PROCUREMENT IS TO SUPPORT THE SPACE COMMUNICATION AND NAVIGATION PROGRAM IMPLEMENT ITS RESPONSIBILITIES. THESE RESPONSIBILITIES CAN BE DIVIDED IN TWO AREAS:  SPECTRUM MANAGEMENT AND PROGRAM MANAGEMENT.  WITHIN THE SPECTRUM MANAGEMENT AREA, THE SCAN PROGRAM IS THE DESIGNATED AUTHORITY FOR THE AGENCY TO SUPPORT THE AGENCY AND THE U.S. COMMERCIAL SPACE COMMUNICATION INDUSTRY FOR SPECTRUM ALLOCATIONS AND ASSIGNMENTS THROUGH LEADERSHIP AND COORDINATION WITH NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL SPECTRUM MANAGEMENT ORGANIZATIONS.  WITHIN THE PROGRAM MANAGEMENT AREA, THE SCAN PROGRAM IS THE DESIGNATED AUTHORITY FOR MAINTAINING OPERATIONAL READINESS OF SPACE COMMUNICATION AND NAVIGATION CAPABILITY TO NASA MISSIONS AND ENHANCING SUCH CAPABILITY THROUGH MATURATION OF TECHNOLOGY, DEVELOPMENT OF NEW SYSTEMS AND LEADING THE DEVELOPMENT OF INTERNATIONAL STANDARDS IN SPACE COMMUNICATION AND NAVIGATION.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF OTHER FUNCTIONS THIS CONTRACT IS FOR (R&D) PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTCHNOLOGY) AND IS FOR THE PURCHASE OF SUPPORT SERVICES FOR ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE THE NASA GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER (GSFC) CONDUCTS A COMPREHENSIVE RESEARCH AND TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM DIRECTED TOWARDS OBSERVING, MONITORING, CHARACTERIZING, MODELING, UNDERSTANDING, AND ADVANCING KNOWLEDGE OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE.  THE RESEARCH PROGRAM IS AIMED AT UNDERSTANDING THE STRUCTURE, DYNAMICS, AND RADIATIVE PROPERTIES OF CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, AND PRECIPITATION; UNDERSTANDING ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY, ESPECIALLY THE ROLE OF NATURAL AND ANTHROPOGENIC TRACE SPECIES ON THE OZONE BALANCE IN THE STRATOSPHERE AND TROPOSPHERE; IMPROVING SHORT AND MEDIUM TERM NUMERICAL WEATHER PREDICTION; UNDERSTANDING THE INFLUENCE OF SOLAR VARIABILITY ON THE EARTH'S CLIMATE; AND ADVANCING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF THE EARTH'S ATMOSPHERE INCLUDING ITS INTERACTION WITH THE EARTH SURFACE.  SCIENTISTS IDENTIFY REQUIREMENTS FOR ATMOSPHERIC OBSERVATIONS VIA SATELLITE MISSIONS AND SUB-ORBITAL INSTRUMENTATION.  SCIENTISTS CONCEIVE, DESIGN, DEVELOP, AND IMPLEMENT OPTICAL, MICROWAVE, RADAR, AND LIDAR TECHNOLOGIES FOR REMOTE SENSING OF THE ATMOSPHERE.  SCIENTISTS FURTHER CONDUCT FIELD MEASUREMENTS FOR SATELLITE SENSOR CALIBRATION AND DATA VALIDATION, AND CARRY OUT MODELING ACTIVITIES FOR ATMOSPHERIC RADIATIVE TRANSFER, CLIMATE, CLOUDS, AEROSOLS, CHEMISTRY AND TRANSPORT OF TRACE SPECIES, AND IN GENERAL THE DEVELOPMENT OF NEXT-GENERATION EARTH SYSTEM MODELS.

column76:
Background
 a. The Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) previously undertook an initiative in Veterans Integrated Service Network (VISN) 1 as part of a Department-wide, uniform planning process which uses an integrated approach to services and facility planning.
 b. This Task Order intends to follow on from that previous work to clarify assumptions that should be considered in completing master planning documents for all facilities in VISN 1 including updates to the original five Medical Center Master Plan documents completed under a previous task order.
 
 Purpose
 a. This Task Order to complete the comprehensive services and facility planning for VISN 1 will:
 i. Provide validated and adjusted workload allocations by market, sub-market, and facility using Baseline FY12 data to determine market demand for VHA, VBA, and NCA services across the VHA VISN 1 footprint. Review and update the integrated service and facility planning previously accomplished for VISN 1 to reflect updated utilization data and to confirm the viability of assumptions made during Phase 1. Update the previously completed deliverables to address workload change of more than 25% of previous projections.
 ii. Expand planning horizon to include 2017 (short term) 2022 (10-year, intermediate term) with sensitivity to 2032 (20-year, long term)
 iii. Revise assumptions for planning consistent with  Assumptions  section of this SOW. 
 iv. Provide a Health Services Delivery Plan for all Markets in VISN 1 to include a comprehensive list of capital projects for all facilities in the VISN 1 footprint to complete the transfer from current status to ideal.  These market-level plans will drive facility development and investment within each market area. Provide narrative, tabular, and graphic documents which can be used to guide the development of Major, Minor, NRM and other project types for submission and review in the new VHA Capital Asset Master Plan (CAMP) process and in the VA-level Strategic Capital Investment Plan (SCIP) process for all VHA facilities in the VISN.
 v. Complete the master planning documents for the remaining 6 medical centers consistent with the assumptions and end state and update the previously completed master plans consistent with the assumptions and the end state.  Update the previously completed Facility Master Plans to address workload change of more than 25% of previous projections.
 vi.Develop strategies and plans to identify challenging or sensitive public relations is- sues associated with the implementation of the proposed Market Plans and to propose methodologies for addressing concerns that will likely be raised by stakeholders.
 b.For this task order, the services and facility planning will include VHA, VBA and NCA facilities.

This mission includes the programmatic and technology development activities for Programmable Objective Encryption Technologies (POET), Advanced Cryptographic Module (ACM), COMSEC/TRANSEC (Communications Security / Transmission Security), Network Satellite Security, Video Transmission Technology, Lightweight Transportable Secure Cell Phone Switch, Secure Wireless Tactical Radio Network, Soldier Tactical Internet (TI) Device, in support of the Global War on Terrorism (GWOT), Foreign Military Sales (FMS), Non-traditional customers, PMs (Program Managers) and PEOs (Program Executive Offices). Cryptographic Modernization Project Management Office (CM PMO) is continuously increasing technology and product development as Project Leader in several Joint Service programs to include JUICE, IFF, Cross Domain Solution (CDS) and POET.
